"More escape from reality required","Weeney man strikes again.  I was playing around with my character sheet and decided, just for yucks, to produce a histogram of my number of skills at each skill level.  Having done that I was immiediately compelled to see if there was a reasonable statistical formula which mirrored the general distribution which I happened to have.  Having found that I decided, gee wouldn't this be convenient for generating NPCs.

Of course having had all this fun with math and numbers I will be the first to admit that the following chart is complete crap.  However, knowing that up front it may still be useful.  The idea behind the chart is that you would start at one of two places:
  a.. If you select the highest ranking skill that you want an NPC to have you would look across the second row of the chart until you found that number.  Notice how there are no entries less than six.  The assumption is that freshly generated characters with NO experience could have ONE skill at a rank six.  Having found the correc column you now read down from there and each cell below lists the number of skills that the character will have at that level.  See massive disclaimer below at this point.  Following the skill histogram are three cells which describe the TLF required to have that distribution of skills.  Note that the columns are all setup to describe characters who have one and only one skill of their highest level.  See massive disclaimer two at this point.
  b.. If you select the total TLF that you want the NPC to have read across the row marked TLF to find the largest number less than the desired TLF and then read up the column to find the skill distribution.
MASSIVE DISCLAIMER ONE:  Sigmunds skill distribution looked nothing like the one described here.  The interesting thing was that ON AVERAGE it tracked this distribution fairly closely, the differences tended to sum out to zero and the TLF was generally in line.  One thing in noticed was that Sigmund has slightly more skills at his highest rank than the profile and has a big bump (as a % of the model) at rank ten because it is a nice looking number (something models are bad at modelling).  However the results were close enough that I'll bet it is fine as a quick starting point for NPCs.

MASSIVE DISCLAIMER TWO:  The chart listed below only shows values for selected points and the gaps between these values are rather large.  For example if your TLF is 32 what does this mean?  Well it means you PROBABLY have at least one nine and you PROBABLY do not have a ten but the again you may.  This stuff is only a baseline.

MASSIVE DISCLAIMER THREE:  This whole shebang is based on my experience with Sigmund who is a generalist.  It may be that characters like Dora had a thirteen when there TLF was twenty.  I don't know.

One further step.

Since TLF does not seem to be a terribly informative number for people to talk about I extended the chart to include your primary factor.  To use this you must decide what general model your character runs under:
  a.. Generalist (this is Sigmund) - your primary factor (if it can be called that) accounts for about 20% of your TLF.
  b.. Class based character - your primary factor (if it can be called that) accounts for about 40% of your TLF.
  c.. Specialist - your primary factor (if it can be called that) accounts for about 60% of your TLF.
  d.. Extreme Specialist - your primary factor (if it can be called that) accounts for about 80% of your TLF.
Based on this categorization you can then look up your primary factor and from that derive a TLF and operate as above.  One of the things I noticed (which is consistent with experience) is that at low levels you are really encouraged to be a specialist or you will be useless and at very high levels anyone who is still a specialist would have to have a character sheet that was very strange indeed.

Just as an example Sigmund's highest factor is KIF however being an extreme generalist this factor does not dominate compared to his other factors.  Sigmunds KIF is a little bigger than 118.5 which would indicate by the model that he has a TLF of 69.3.  Well, he doesn't have one that large but it is not off by orders of magnitude so we will skip over that for the moment. The model indicates his highest skill is a 12 (true) and gives rough distributions for his skills below that.  The model does not say which factors these ranks are in so it is no longer relevant whether he is a specialist or a generalist.  The distributions are not exact but are close enough for jazz (+/- < 100%, +/- <33% in many cases).

I have a feeling that the biggest hole in the chart is that PCs tend to have one skill which they consider vital to their character and thus pump up way beyond what any statistical model would predict.  Is this true.  In the example of Sigmund he has had a 12 SCF Perception for a long time now since early on he just rammed eps into it every run becuase he thought it was vital to his character (he has somewhat moved on since then to a slightly broader base).  In the example of Dora above (I think this is accurate) did she have many skills that were way up there or only Ax?

As an interesting question ( and the reason I ran the numbers so high) if Ariock has a 15 sword is he a generalist with a 300 PCF and a TLF up around 150 or is he less generalized with a PCF >400 or is his TLF lower and he (like many PCs) reflects an aberation from a classical waterfall skill model (or is the model crap).

Another revolting question.  Mordenaith, didn't I hear you mention that you had a 15 Abjuration at one point?  Do specialists tend to have a higher highest skill for the same TLF than generalists.  I would believe that.  (For the moment I consider you a specialist, though not an extreme one, Mordenaith).

Anyway.  It all means nothing.  I was just having fun playing with numbers.

         
