"RE: The run","I'm gonna wait for the answers to Jim's questions before submitting my own
numbers.  (Though E-man looks much prettier, after I spent all yesterday
working on his character sheet.)  (He is 23, BTW.)  (Maybe 24.  Does anyone
know the date on which we departed?)


As to reviews:

Level 1: The Gate.
     Short and sweet.  Could have been a little longer, twistier, or more
hazardous (perhaps a creature or two, or maybe just a Nameless Dread.. some
reason to hurry) but it *was* just the doorway, after all.

Level 2: The Happy Hills
     A little short, but I think part of that was due to our, um, ""direct""
approach.  E-man was unsatisfied with the elegance of the solution, but
that was a party choice, not a GM thing.  And the greenthieves were not
menacing enough.  Of course, it *is* better to lull your opponent into
overconfidence while drawing him deeper into the trap, and this level was
probably intened to double as a temporary hiding place from magic-based
threats. (I betting Logos did this one.)

Level 3: The River
     A fine level.  E-man felt a little like Chicken Little, but it was a
wonderful threat and barrier all at once.  Kudos also to Kilsorana, without
whom the party would have been much smaller at the end of the level, and
Trevain, without whom we would have been much wetter and more battered.

Level 4: Super Mario Brothers
     An excellent presentation of a video-game level.  Again, a wonderful
threat and barrier at once. Loved the descriptions of the spiny normans and
the ooze-balls.  I, too, was annoyed by the puzzle, but I think that's a
personal thing; it wasn't complex enough to let E-man's patterning skills
really shine.  As frustrating as it was, he enjoyed the challenge.  Nice to
see a little of Falstaff doing the stuff that made him great.

Level 5: Chutes and Ladders
     Nasty, brutish, and short. Nice and devious.  I liked the use of the
people as part of the trap/solution.  E-man's patience is beginning to
fray, and this level was designed to take advantage of that.  In addition,
it is very hard on any water-tuned sorts who might have survived Level 3 in
particularly good shape.  (It looks like there is an elemental progression
going on here; I'll have to review my basic metaphysics if I don't freeze
to death first.)  E-man was shocked by Sigmund's callousness here, and I
expect it is a side of the little guy he hadn't seen before.  I suspect we
may also encounter more problems on the way out because of our actions
here.  

Level 6: Mountains of Misery
     Far too cold.  Another endurance challenge, weakening any fire-types
who might have thrived on the level before.  I'm already trying to figure
out how to wear my tent as a robe, and thinking about weaving mittens. 
Brr!


Anyone got a date for the next run?

                                                                       
