"Sunbane for fun and profit","More trouble from the Mythmeister...

I've been thinking about those sunbane devices (okay: ""Summon Sunlight 
devices"") that we discussed (briefly) a run or two back.

While the 'pez dispenser' idea is an amusing one, I can't see Kilsorana 
wanting that many effigies of herself (at least, incomplete ones) roaming 
the streets and swearing at undead.  Besides, using her face could 
possibly make her a component in a device-destroying ritual, and 
Kilsorana can make enemies nicely on her own. (Besides, says E-man, it's 
just not dignified!)

(""Tis a silly place."")

I had been thinking of maybe a candle-driven lantern as a device.  Have 
ordinary mages make candles, wihch would provide the chief power for the 
rite.  Add a candle to a lantern, light it, and chant your little chant.  
Light blazes out, undead thingies turn to dust or stone, whatever makes 
the GM happy.

(Somehow, I am reminded of the frozen laser in 'Real Genius'.)

This lets us seperate the permanent, tricky, and salable stuff (the 
actual summoning of sunlight) from our still-tricky, but requiring mass 
production stuff.  Trade secrets are protected without any of us forced 
to work the assembly line at the widget factory.

Candles would need to be strong in beeswax (big Nature component), I'm 
thinking, with probably mixtures on herbs, spices, and oils.  Wicks could 
be woven with Weaver magic for whatever binding or (gasp) abjuration 
seems appropriate.  I am thinking of the lanterns as glass spheres held 
in a framework of wire, possibly mithril or platinum or silver.  Possibly 
gems in the framewoark to refract the light.

Whatever the construction (or nature) of the devoce, I think there are 
probably a few design constraints.

 1. Must be usuable by anyone (or anyone not undead).  Probably much 
better in the hands of a mage or priest.

 2. Should be able to operate, at least at a basic level, for twelve 
hours.  No sense leaving our monster-hunters in the dark any time before 
dawn.

 3. Should have at least a simple detect/react to undead; not necessarily 
seeking them out, but probably glowing brighter in their presence.


Comments? Complaints? Cries of dismay?

Feel free to forward, as well.

                                 -Myth.




