I am writing down some random views I have about reality shifting and how it
relates to the skills I have.  This is in order to clarify the thoughts I
have and as a way to figure out where I can go from here.

JIM'S RECOLLECTION OF THE WORLD

So far we have talked about reality alteration using a number of models:

Simplest Model  - Objective Reality

At one level we talk about reality as if it's properties were stored
somewhere.  In this view each property of reality has one and only one
value.  For example, things always fall down.  This value may be conditional
with reference to a locale, such as things always fall down except in the
Abyss, but it is always delegated by a clear set of rules.  I like to view
this as the Newtonian model of reality.

Another Model - Consensus Reality

In this model of reality all of the properties of reality exist only in the
conversation between people (actually Context Generating Beings [CGBs]).
Some conversations are more fundamental than others, like things fall down,
and these conversations are so ingrained into our world view that they take
on a life of their own.  In cases like these we can tend to objectify the
conversations and deal with them as entities in and of themselves.  Thus it
can make grammatic sense to talk about altering The Consensus or The
Consensus exerting a restorative force.

In the advanced stages of this model we adopt the view of aggregate reality
perception in which each individual CGB exists in its own self-generated
reality which may differ in microscopic ways from anyone else's.  In this
model, concepts such as planes can be seen as a local clumping in which the
deviation of any one entity from the norm is small compared to it's
""distance"" from any other clump.  We could say that the member's of a plane
share a common perception becuase their world views are so similar.  We
could also say that the great mass of consensus around the common concepts
of the plane form a restorative force. The result of this force is that,
when an individual strongly changes their view around one of these
fundamental concepts, either their view is restored back to the group
consensus or the group consensus is drawn to the new view.  This all depends
on the force of the CGB asserting the new view and the mass of consensus
against which this CGB is acting.  In some sense it also depends on the
reasonableness of the new viewpoint in relation to other beliefs in the
consensus (it is not odd for a human to float in mid-air if they are an
evoker).

Another Model - Patterned Reality

An alternate model for viewing reality which exists at the same level is
that of patterned reality.  In this model every CGB  generates a reality
which surrounds them, just as above, and this reality differs in microscopic
ways from the reality of any other entity.  The difference in the models is
in the view of the reality characteristics.  In the patterned reality, each
set of common precepts (or conversations) which is shared by a set is viewed
as a class which all of the objects of the set inherit from.  In this way
being a creature of the prime is a class which humans derive from and human
is a class which Tolnians derive from, etc.  Thus we view the the set of all
CGB's less as a set of discrete objects and more as a tree of shared
properties.

In fact, in this model, one would be faced with the philosophical question,
""If two entities share completely the same inherritance tree of classes then
are they in fact one entity?""  In some ways, however, beyond a few
metaphysical questions like the prior, the difference between this and the
above is semantic.  In other senses, it is very much akin to the
philosophical-physical paradox of wave-particle duality.

The way in which the difference between these two models is less than
semantic is in the subjective perception of how easy it is to effect change.
In the consensus model, changing one's reality is merely a matter of
changing one's belief.  There is the danger expressed that if you change in
too radical a manner you will be orphaned from the consensus with which you
were associated and cast adrift.  There is also the restorative force which
acts to prevent casual drift from severing ties with the consensus group of
attachment.  Both of these appear, however, to be surmountable by a strong
will.  In the patterned reality model it appears more that the
characteristics which define you are universal patterns which are harder for
you to control.

If, for example, you are a human and you wish to change one of the
characteristics which you posses which is inherently human (say having two
arms) in the patterned model it appears that you would need to either change
this characteristic for all humans (daunting) or reparent yourself to some
class other than human.  In the consensus model it would appear that all you
would have to do is change this characteristic in yourself and then convince
the consensus that it was normal.  The conversation human seems much more
fluid in this model.

In some sense, we can view the difference as moot.  The pattern-viewed
person is really reparenting to a new class which they are creating as a
subclass of human but then explaining to the consensus why these new
subclass-humans are not unusual.  The consensus-viewed person, in convincing
the consensus-group that this is normal is redefining the concept of
humanness.  Despite the fact that they are compatible, however, the flavor
of each seems to indicate that consensus-viewed manipulation is easier but
more dangerous and pattern-viewed manipulation is harder but more
far-reaching.

Anyway, that's the impression I get.


