Answers to some of my questions by Alex:

>
>About the micro-reality rod:
>
>After having done some research in the wizard council's library:
>Do I have any idea if this is a named/recognized item?

It is not.

>Was I able to infer anything about it's design/purpose?

Yes.  It is a reality isolation that is separate from and unaffected by
agreement reality shifts.
Used as a benchmark by Preceptors in Wild Magic Research.

>I actually have fairly high ranks in research[6] (I was in info mode) as
>well as ranks in planar lore[6] and discipline lore[7] INF[85].
>If I wanted to use this rod to build a trap, how effective would
>it be.  The
>purpose for the trap would be as follows:  modify the rod so that it was a
>one-way reality isolation at the tip.  Whack Rismaeon with the rod sucking
>him into the micro-reality created and trapping him there.  If I think this
>would hold him that would be cool.  If I think this would hold him but not
>for more than a few minutes/seconds that would be cool too.

Okay.  It isn't designed as a container, it isn't built to hold anything.
You would have to ""turn"" Rhysmaeon into something that could live in a
stick.  It is a stick not a universe- and it is a universe that is a stick.
Does that make sense?

Given that you could shove him in there somehow- he would get out as soon as
he figured out the nature of his prison- which would take from 3 counts
minimum(he would need to cast three Disciplines to get out minimum and let's
just say he gets lucky and does one count disciplines.  Very unlikely but
possible with good dice luck)  to seconds to 10 seconds tops.

> The next
>question would be, if I take the rod somewhere else outside of the ward
>control room and he escapes from the micro-reality is he in that place or
>can he choose to where he returns?  If he is there then I could
>give the rod
>to Jim and he could take it to fairy.

He would have to use the interface between the rod and this agreement
reality which happens to be the outside surface of the rod so where the rod
goes the gate goes.

>This of course assumes that the rod does not have some other purpose which
>is better or would conflict with this.

Yep. It doesn't seem to.

