"Re: Shapeshifters","Probably a very poor and Sigmund centric view of what happened.  Also , this
is all from memory so I am not sure how accurate it is (my memory is not as
sturdy as most):

When last you left us we had firmly decided to ambush a large train of
zombies and ghouls which outnumberd us by aproximately1000 to 1.  We had
discovered a point along there path in which they would pass through a large
ravine with small berms spread across.  We were setting up our ambush there.

The aproximate force opposing us was (as best I can remember) about 10,000
zombies & ghouls with a number of Ogres along.  These were lead by a large
number of Necromancers who also had about 20 lethar as forward scouts and a
large invisible dragon as a shock troop.  I forget whether we had
established that some of the Necromantic forces were death lords or not.

As a side note during the entire setup Sigmund was under the impression that
the invisible Dragon which led the troops was 20' from snout to tail.  It
was not until he actually engaged it in hand-to-hand combat that he
discovered that it was 20' from the ground to the top of it's head and about
80' from snout to tail.  At this point it was too late to change my tactics.
Anyway, this is the problem with fighting invisible creatures.

The lethar where leading the troops (as scouts) so Sigmund. Kor'Keth, D'Jan
and Muriel set up an ambush line at the first berm (an earthy rise excellant
for hiding behind).  D'Jan and Muriel where at the extremes of the Ravine
actually part way up the ravine wall.  The remainder of the forces where
either hidden behind the second wall (Kheldar, Mordenaith, Justicar and
Arak) or hidden behind Kilsorana who had cleverly transformed herself into a
rock outcropping.  Khalid and the StormLord had taken to the air and were
brewing up some nasty weather (a slow but dramatic process involving some
very impressive 100 mile diameter cyclical cloud patterns).  D'Jan had been
given a number of SunBane triggers by Mordenaith in an effort to make
somebody besides himself be ""the beacon which draws all of the fire while
the rest of us act"".

Well that was the plan.  What actually happened was that the lethar came
ahead of the troops in a skirmish line and by sheer luck we noticed that the
dragon was not far behind them.  Some of the lethar where also moving along
the near vertical cliff face like nasty slobbering death spiders (insert
Alex's trademark Lethar face and hand gestures here).  In a brilliant
tactical assesment D'Jan determined that even if he hid from them they would
easily see the back troops before we could ax them quietly and the dragon
would surely notice that so it was much more productive to take them out in
a big flashy way.

Becoming visible D'Jan waved his arms and started shouting.  When they were
all straing directly at him he let them have it with both of the SunBane
triggers.  I forget the exact breakdown but he toasted quite a number of
them (though not all) in a very short amount of time.  This is when the
proverbial shit started hitting the fan.

Sigmund (still under the impression that 20' tall meant the dragon was about
triple human size) decided that since our cover was blown it was time to
take the dragon out before he could overrun the mages.  Thus the invisible
3' tall creature started charging towards where he thought the invisible 20'
tall creature was with the intent to do bodily harm.  Meanwhile Arak, seeing
at least one non-toasted lethar charging towards D'Jan began his own charge
to back up his diminuative friend.  At the same time Mordenaith and Kheldar
were both casting there won respective longer term spells.  I apologize
E-Man because I do not remember your actions at this part of the battle
(although how could I forget them later).

Meanwhile Khalid has finally explained to the StormLord that you actually
can have storms without using water, they are called sandstorms.  The
StormLord, being a bit of a traditionalists has a little trouble with this
idea but decides to give it a whirl.

At about this point Sigmund gets close to the dragon and they both start
swinging around looking for each other.  The dragon seems to find Sigmund
first and breathes a huge cone of fire which Sigmund is barely able to
escape by leaping almost 20' vertically into the air (do not try this at
home - do not ask me to repeat that feat).  As he is contemplating what to
do next the dragon takes a swipe with his wing and sends sigmund flying into
the dirt (most painfully I might add).

At roughly the same time both Mordenaith and Kheldars spells go off.
Mordenaith takes a large rock and accelerates it into the Dragon (which had
cleverly revealed itself by breathing on me).  The rock was accelerated so
fast that it approached cannon ball speeds and punched a large hole through
the dragon. Kheldar was taking a less direct approach and had summoned all
of the remaining lethar into a warded summoning circle.  They were ecstatic
about the nearness of tasy humans until they found they could not penetrate
the wards.  This frustration turned to even greater displeasure when Kheldar
pulled out the Orb of Souls and started draining their very existence.  This
small portion of the battle proceded at a much less frantic pace as Kheldar
liesurley dispatched the remaining scouts.

Meanwhile back at the dragon Sigmund was madly healing himself after the
painful impact with the ground which would have made him a very tasty target
had not E-Man intervened.  Erithmaen had been flying towards the battle site
on his trusty carpet and decided, for reasons he will have to explain to do
an acrobatic dismount directly in front of the dragon and allow his carpet
to fly away.  Needless to say this show of bravado distracted the dragon
momentarily.  The dragon decided to breath on the obviously dangerous new
target who escaped by a thin margin with his life.  Using this distraction,
and the fact that the dragons head was turned Sigmund charged forward and
lept onto the dragons back.  This was about the point where I discovered
that I was fighting something the size of my house (that's right 39 westlake
road is about 80' by 30' by 20' at the roof).  Oh well, too late to change
now.  I started to climb the neck.

As we were dealing with the first 15 or so members of the 10,000 creature
army Khalid and the StormLord started at the other end of the column.
Having whipped the winds up to a reasonable velocity they started a huge
wall of flying sand moving down the ravine.  Khalid threw in a few dust
devils to toss about the siege towers and large creatures while the
StormLord began peppering things with lightning bolts from an altitude of
two or three miles up.  A wyvern mounted death lord attempted to ascend to
the heights to see the cause of this unusual weather but did not make it
very far before becoming cajun blackened death lord.  The loss of the rear
gaurd and the large flying objects, 100 mph winds and choking dust did not
have a good impact on moral but unfortunately for them zombies are stupid.
Which I suppose is just as well since the didn't have anywhere to run to
anyway.

Back at the front combat Sigmund was rapidly climbing the dragons neck.  In
order to attempt to combat a creature of this size I enlarged my own size
until I was 12' tall but I was still a blip compared to the dragon.  At the
point I reached the head the dragon decided to slam its head against the
ground squashing me flat.  Having very little time to react I stabbed my
shortsword into the dragons ear, which was about 4' in diameter, returned to
my normal size and crawled inside, converting my sword into its full spear
length in the process.  This did not have a pleasant effect on the dragons
brain.

I apologize once again becuase I know some rather important things were
happening during this period but I am afraid I was a little distratcted.  In
any case at that point the dragons head hit the ground with me now firmly
wedged in its skull.  I took a lot of shaking but was able to keep my
position and burrowed my way in until I carved out enough of the vital stuff
to stop it from moving.  This of course involved the traditional rearing up
to its full height followed by the head falling with a great thud (another
painful process since I was still inside it).  After that we return to my
previous e-mail.  The dust settled on the battle.  I was completely
exhausted and not at my sharpest mentally.  Somehow I had gotten it into my
head that I needed to pull to four fang teeth out of the dragons head as
trophies and, unlike everyone else, I did not notice the approaching mile
high wall of dust until it was upon us.  Everyone else retreated into a
convenient cave (which may have been of your creation).  While the storm,
with Khalid and the StormLord riding it, passed overhead.

The End

