"Gaming","Just thought I would throw in my two cents after Chris's articulate e-mail.

It seems to me that there are two fairly seperate issues:
1.    Coming up with a way that will allow us to leave the third epoch and
arrive in the fifth epoch in a place and manner of our own choosing and
managing the reintegration into reality so that we maintain our sanity.
2.    Convincing the fifth epoch to let us back in.

All of the analysis that Chris presented in his e-mail seems to me to boil
down to one basic principle.

Let us assume that at some point a great discipline casting was invoked
which asserted order on a previously less ordered universe.  This discipline
casting by its existance forms a barrier between the way of looking at
things before the casting and the way of looking at things after the
casting.

Since we grew up (for the most part) in the way of looking at things after
the casting and furthermore since this way of looking at things is a causal
ordered kind of view we tend to think of our epoch as after the third epoch.
This is also consistent with the 'person standing at the end is the winner'
viewpoint which requires us to assume we are latter if we want to believe
that our casting succeeded.

Anyway, the actual temporal ordering is less relevant.  My point is that by
the very fact that the fifth epoch is formed by the continuing support of
this discipline casting it will resist our re-entry.  Specifically the
consensus of the fifth epoch (lets call it consensus-5) must oppose the
existence of any being which claims to be able to handle/perceive/conceive
of the opposed viewpoint (lets call it the alien-view).  The more an entity
advocates or describes the alien-view the more the consensus-5 must oppose
that entity out of self defense.  Any such entity could be treated as a
virus which would slowly eat away at the strength of the discipline casting
and eventually cause holes in it.

One possible viewpoint is that if we were to travel to the epoch-3 and
return with all of our memories and then tell people all about what we had
seen we would be doing the work of the gate in making the Slaad more present
in epoch-5.  Even worse if we were to get something in epoch-3 (like a kick
ass magic item) and bring it back with us we would definately be strengthen
the slaad position and hence weakening the barrier of consensus-5.

I suspect in the face of that consensus-5 would fight back.  BTW:
consensus-5 could be viewed as an abstract representation of the will
momentum from the discipline cast but I think it is also a convenient term
for the set of major players who have a vested interest in keep epoch-5
distinct from its past.

In any case to address this point (#2 in my first list) I see a few options:

1.    The most successful tact may be to not return at all but to prevent us
from having left in the first place.  After all we are in the chaos time, we
should take advantage of it.  It seems to me that the consensus-5 would be
perfectly happy to let us in if we were willing to say the following, ""Well
the Slaad gate almost had us and we wrestled in some sort of NULL space for
a while but in the end we rejected the Slaad destination and were able to
divert our teleport to a new location.""

The mind boggling question is if we do all sorts of things in epoch-3 to
repell ourselves from having come there then what will happen to us after we
never came?  The answer is we won't care because to our selves in epoch-5 it
will never have happened.  Ignore the apparent paradoxes and they will go
away.

This seems to me the strategy the consensus-5 would most prefer.

2.    Next best might be to treat our exit and re-entry as pure
transportationbut to tack on the following explanation, ""The thing that
makes epoch travel hard is not the going there or the coming back but the
integration and re-integration of reality shifts.  When we went to epoch-3
we were never fully integrated and so we could never fully interact with
anyone there.  This was demonstrated by the way we kept our own physical
laws with us.  When we returned we were unable to reconcile the world view
of epoch-3 with that of epoch-5 and so in order to re-integrate we had to
lock this section of our memories under tight mental blocks.""  This strategy
once again insures the consensus-5 that we will not be going around
spreading the virus of epoch-3-speak.  On the other hand it does allow the
possibility (interesting for us - scary for the consensus-5) that we might
be able to drag tidbits out of this locked store at a later date.  This
approach also has precendence since this is how I am saying that
Olactalan-Tlovanu was able to translate forward to become Nureyev in the
current reality.  In the face of this conversation the consensus-5 might
counter-assert that if, after reintegrating,  we ever did open the locks
enough to adopt the alien-view we would automatically be catapulted out of
the reality back into epoch-3 even if nobody else knew about it.

My opinion is that the consensus-5 would buy this with a little grumbling.

3.    A final possibility is that we could find some way in which our group
is so unique that our doing this journey does not in any way set a
precendant for anyone else.  This is kind of a weak argument and I think we
would have to be able to package it very convincingly for the consensus-5 to
buy it but it certainly gives us the most freedom.

Anyway, that is what occured to me.  What do other people think?

As far as my opinion I think 1 or 2 are both workable for me.  I am very
interested in having memories of the past but I think I already have enough
ammunition in place with my sordid past so that I don't need to push it on
this point.  #1 would probably be not only the most likely to succeed in my
eyes but also the biggest mind fuck and that has some perverse attraction as
well.

On a related note I cannot do the 20th.  Sorry.

