  OK, here is my input on the situation.  Chris has given Fortu construction
a good amount of thought, but because the Fortu are more related to Pookie's
character than mine, nothing that I say as ""Kheldar"" should be taken as
gospel, (or maybe what Kheldar says is the way Fortu were constructed before
the Fortu Reality Shift).  What I can say is that I've done several things
with Alex that have given Kheldar ranks in Fortu
design/construction/analysis/repair.  That should absolutely add plusses to
Sigmund's healing.


  Let me describe Kheldar's concept of Fortu construction, particularly
Sigmund's construction.


  Only the earliest Fortu models would have been constructed on an
Anthropomorphic basis.  Certainly by Series 3 we would have discarded the
placement of components based on where those control centers would have been
in an evolved biological organism.  The ""mammary"" modules on the female
units are a perfect example of this.  In most cases the ""mammary""
protrusions on a ""female"" Fortu were memory storage.


  By Series 5 we would have gone to a distributed architecture, something
similar to RAID 5 storage (Hot swap and multiple parity drives), all
critical components located in the densest part of the Fortu - the main body
cavity.  The Series 5 Ops model was also designed to manipulate Reality
magics.  As such it would have needed to be designed to be resistant to
external Reality changes yet be able to use Reality magics to effect
repairs.  What good would Wizardry or Sorcery based repairs be in a
""Reality"" where there were no patterns or no mana?


  I liken Serreth's design to that of a Borg starship but not quite a T1000
Terminator.  Borg ships aren't as flexible as T1000's but they are highly
resilient.  Serreth was a Will based entity with material aspects.  He was
designed with the ability to re-configure his firmware.  His head, arms, and
legs were as much Hard Drives in a RAID 5 array as they were ""arms"" or
""legs"" or Audio/Video mounts.  His primary systems would have had multiple
control paths - Fortu have no Aorta.  His peripherals were designed to be
replaced.  Frankly, Serreth should have been able to have his head blown
clean off and not lose any memories/data.


  Would he have been unaffected by this attack?  No.  However:


  1). Depending on what percentage of Sigmund was considered ""parity"", he
would be vulnerable to data loss after losing of 20 to 50% of his body mass.
At that point there would be complete loss of data.  Given that backups to
the Ward over the net were part of the design of the Fortu, significant data
loss, even in the face of complete obliteration of form, would have been
highly unlikely (unless, of course, you refused to do backups and
disconnected yourself from the net but no Wizard would instruct his Fortu to
do that).


  2). Any Fortu feature defined as ""peripheral"" or ""firmware"" which had
components physically located on the damaged area would require repair or
replacement.  ""Firmware"" *might* require physical replacement and
programming.  The Series 5 model would probably be on-line faster with
physical repairs, but would ultimately recreate itself to the point
immediately before damage occurred.  Some functions might be temporarily
off-line until replacement.  (can't speed up or can't transverse).


  3).  Since the architecture is distributed, there would be processor
degradation.  The physical effect would be the minuses given to people who
are more than 100% wounded.  Some functions might be temporarily off-line.
(can't speed up or can only double speed instead of quadruple speed; slower;
less endurance).


  4). System Shock would need to be rolled, but would probably not kill the
Fortu if it was failed unless it was a major failure.  It would, however,
cause the Fortu to go Hard while effecting repairs.  A major failure of
system shock would indicate disruption of primary services AND self repair.
(now the separation of soul would also be an issue)


  The biggest issue from Kheldar's standpoint would not be the physical
damage.  Kheldar would (and does) say that he can have Sigmund's physical
form repaired back to ""normal"" within several hours once he gets Sigmund
into the ""shop"".  Kheldar will be far more concerned, however, with the
corruption of data resulting from the possession.  To continue with the
computer analogy, Sigmund has a virus.  And Kheldar as he is now is not the
best programmer in this reality.


  Since I don't think that Sigmund wants Kheldar to bring Rismaeon in for a
consultation, that leaves Falstaff, Ignatious, Logos, possibly Miriel ...and
the two best options, each of which has a major drawback:
  Big Brother, who knows Sigmund better than any other entity OR
  Arioch, whose programming skills are considerable and whose ability to
follow a logic tree is unmatched.


  I think that further discussion is pointless until Kheldar actually has a
chance to examine Sigmund.  I would like to hear Alex's (and Pookie's)
thoughts on the ""effects of damage"" that I listed above.


