Actually, I suppose if I were really building a combat machine I would put
the brain in a reality bubble with only well insulated nerve endings
travelling out into the physical body.  Furthermore I would build the
nervous system as a series of parallel packet networks so that any one
connection from the reality bubble could service all of the sensors and
motors but at the same time any particular network could be dropped out if
an infection was encountered (wildfire virus, chaos stream, meme attack...).
Finally I would put portculis fuses on the reality bubble interface so that
if a massive chaos stream took over the entire body I could drop the whole
thing to prevent core systems damage.  In order to prevent loss of the
isolated sphere I would tether it to a central point using a completely
non-planar connection.  This tether could also be used as a private
communication channel with other entities hooked in the same way if needed.

Come to think of it when I ""dropped"" the body I might as well just convert
it into a completely non-reactive state.  This way, if it manages to
survive, I could locate it using the backdoor tether to connect to some
reality monitor (like a linking ward) and use that to reattach the physical
body back to the reality bubble.

Kind of scary actually.

