"Re: Gaming (D&D) strategy problem - SOLUTION?","I know it is unlike me but I just wanted to introduce a note of reality here.

A Gaurdian can out run a troll.
A Guardian apparently can out run a troll while carrying one dwarf.
While gaurdians are bitchin strong they do acknowledge the concept momentum and
hence a gaurdian will not be able to pull one thousand dwarves as fast as it
could pull one.

Doing some quick calculatios:

Assume 1 dwarf weighs 100 kg (probably more with armour and weapons)

Let us assume also that we have arranged something so that all of the dwarves
travel on a frictionless surface (rollerblades, skis,etc.) but the Guardian
still has traction. Since we probably can arrange lets assume we have four
gaurdians (Kelthi, Trevaine, Gallek, Sigmund).

Also it occurs to me, aren't there only 700 or so dwarves in existence?  I
assume they are not all coming so isn't 500 dwarves a more appropriate number?

Lets adjust our estimate just to be realistic and say a dwarf averages 200kg
after his axe and plate armour are added in (440 lbs.).

Total dwarvish mass 100,000kg = 100 metric tonnes
Probable length of the line of dwarves (1m/dwarf) = 0.5 km

Now here is the biggy, force able to be applied by a Gaurdian:
After you include skills Sigmund in Gaurdian mode probably has a lift of
~1200lbs (call it 5000 Netwons).  This seems small and the biggest question is
what is the efficiency conversion between lifting a weight straight up and
pulling a weight across a frictionless surface.

For the moment lets assume four gaurdians can exert a force of 20,000N.  This
corresponds to a train acceleration of:

a = F / m = 20,000 / 100,0000 = 0.2 m/s^2

Lets say we have a 5km runway (total so 4.5 km of usable space).  Our gaurdian
locomotive can now accelerate its 0.5km long dwarf train in a time of:

using d = v0 * t + 0.5 * a * t^2 with v0=0 we get t = sqrt( d * 2 / a )
sqrt( 4500 * 2 / 0.2) [s] = 212 [s]

I forget what Vardigans will roll rate is but lets say he makes a roll every 5
seconds.
Lets say the effective length of the halls is 5km and the Troll tries to kill
everything in the hall.
We can then calculate the total time from start till leaving the hall (plus
0.5km).

using d = v0 * t + 0.5 * a * t^2 with v0=0 we get t = sqrt( d * 2 / a )
sqrt( (5000 + 500 + 4500) * 2 / 0.2) [s] = 316 [s]

This means that some dwarf will be in the hall for a period of:

316 - 212 = 114 [s] or 23 rolls

OK, this is already starting to look a little shaky.  Why don't I recap the
basic assumptions and then get some better numbers from Alex.

ASSUMPTIONS FOR THE FORTU-DWARF EXPRESS TRAIN

1. We can get all of the dwarves in a line with frictionless feet and none of
them fall down
2. Number of dwarves = 500 {Nd}
3. Average dwarf spacing in a line = 0.5 [m] {Sd}
4. Average dwarf + weapons + armour = 200 [kg] {Md}
5. Average gaurdian fortu effective force = 5000 [N] {Fg}
6. Number of Gaurdians = 4 {Ng}
7. You have a runway to get up to speed on in front of the entrance
8. Length of the runway = 5000 [m] {Lr}
9. The halls of the dead are pretty straight
10. Effective length of the segment of the halls of the dead being travelled =
5000 [m] {Lh}
11. There is space after the exit so you dont slam the freight train into a wall
12. The required frequency of Vardigan's will rolls = 5 [s] {Vf}

Based on this:
Fortu-Dwarf Train Acceleration = ( {Fg} * {Ng} ) / ( {Md} * {Nd} ) = {A}
Distance from start to entrance (minus train length) = {Lr} - {Nd}*{Sd} = {L01}
Distance from entrance to exit (plus train length) = {Lh} + {Nd}*{Sd} = {L02}
Time from start to entrance = sqrt( 2 * {L01} / {A} ) = {T01}
Time from start to exit = sqrt( 2 * {L02} / {A} ) = {T02}
Number of rolls Vardigan needs to make = ( {T02} - {T01} ) / {Vf}
Velocity of the dwarf train at exit = {T02} * {A}

Other than the shear ridiculousness of it, it just might work.

I assume there is also some max speed for Gaurdians (a non-linear HP curve).  In
