Just a little comment from someone who actually worked on trains.  :)  There
is this little issue known as slack action.  Basically it is due to the fact
that a train isn't a single rigid body, but a series of them with a certain
amount of give between each member.  When starting a train the locomotive
pulls the first car, first taking up the slack, then there is a small bump
as the car is quickly accelerated up to the locomotives speed.  This is
experienced at each coupling.  The result is that your Guardian taking off
at a dead run will probably snap his train somewhere in the middle.  Now
since we are dealing with frictionless surfaces we could also assume
unbreakable rope (magical?).  I have no idea about what that means for your
magical noise and reality bending Hoobie Doobies, as that is way out of my
realm.   But with magical rope, and an effort to stretch out the train first
to reduce slack action, you could probably get things going.  The big
problem I see is stopping.  See, this slack action thing works in reverse
too.  Since the guardian is the only breaking force at the end of the
journey, it will stop, and the first dwarf will run up it's slack of rope
(0.5m) and smack into the guardian and then begin it's deceleration.  Then
dwarf 3 into 2, 4 into 3 etc.  This would work, but it is a bit
uncomfortable. Lots of jarring.  However, I remember the dwarf containers
being discussed as spherical or something to eliminate catching on things.
If that is the case, when attempting to stop, you won't just all mush into
each other, you will have a sort of billiard ball effect, where say 4 hits
into 3 and shoots off at a 45degree angle, with the added bonus that they
are all tied together and thus pulled around.  End result, big old jumble at
the end.  I assume the dwarves will be protected in their cases, but the
guardian will have a couple bruises, I would imagine.

