"Re: Gaming (D&D) strategy problem - SOLUTION?","I have done some preliminary calculations and come up with the following:

With out using time-dilation Sigmund-Gaurdian should be able to
grab-run-check-and-return a 3 dwarf package (sans armour) in 6 counts.  This is
based on
1 count to grab
1 count to pass the first barrier
15 counts to dash 75m and jump the pit
1 count to pass the second barrier
1 count to drop and reverse
1 count to pass the second barrier
15 counts to dash 75m and jump the pit
1 count to pass the first barrier
---
36 counts or 7.2 seconds (for a 150m dash - for comparison the world's record
for 100m dash is 9.85 seconds and they dont have gelatinous barriers or 240kg
weights to contend with)

At a time dilation of 6:1 this makes 1.2 seconds per trip.

Unfortunately even using all my tricks this burns 11 END per second which means
a one minute insertion burns aproximately 660 END (which I don't quite have) and
(with four gaurdians) moves 600 dwarves.

In order to keep this up for a sustained period we would need about 8 hours rest
(to regain the exhaustion) and then we could repeat the process.

Actually, if I can use both reduced endurence for high rank (caution
rules-optimizer at work) and ranks of critical to reduce endurence then the burn
rate drops to 5 END per second which means a one minute insertion burns only 300
END (leaving me 55% exhausted).

This requires only 4 hours between insertions to make steady state and thus it
would only take 73 hours (or 18 trips over 3 days) to move the dwarves.  Luckily
Gaurdian Fortu are really stupid and don;t mind boring work like this at all.

I think the best route for optimizing this is to work on increasing the number
of dwarves per trip.  This solution requires Vartigan to make 18 minutes worth
of rolls but they are spread out over a good amount of time.

Oh, the other thing is if their were an easy way to regain the exhaustion faster
than 4 hours of rest that would cut down on the total time even though it would
not change the number of rolls required.  Still, I think three days is a bargain
for moving the dwarvish army so I suspect any ""loud magics"" would not be worth
the risk here.

