Wherever we do it, and however we do it, interfacing with that event will
put us in dangerous space, and appropriate (i.e., world-spanning paranoid)
precautions should be taken.  If we can arrange it, some sort of extreme
slow motion might give us an advantage in defending against things from the
other side.  We'll need it anyway, just to see Sigmund.

Also, I am under the impression that some events are particularly hard to
divine, given the large numbers of interfacing defenses, restrictions,
powers and egos in play.  I suspect our walk on the wild side of Marden may
be one of those.  We should account for this.

On the Kilsorana front, the pattern we used was her True Name, as given by
the gods of her people.  That should be a darn sight more accurate than any
description of her we might obtain through Read Pattern.  (I was also under
the impression that we defined the spell, at least to the outside Reality,
as 'summoning her from the instant just before she was destroyed.)

With Sigmund, we could certainly use Restore to Pattern (or the simpler
Restore Pattern skill) to provide a matrix for the gap that Sigmund's
natural healing mechanism could then re-pattern and incorporate into his
form.  (The equivalent of using coral for missing bone mass and letting the
body recalcify it.)  In fact, I would recommend that use of the spell, in
that Sigmund will otherwise be working around the fact that he is leaking
integrity all over the floor, and may be too busy dying to recover at all.

For his pattern, we have several options.  First of all, he (unlike
Kilsorana) is already here, just terribly hurt.  We don't really need to do
tricky things with time and space to get a pattern for him, as he and his
pattern are standing right in front of us.  If we want to splint his
pattern, and provide a reminder of its unwounded state and a guide for it's
recovery, we can certainly do that.  It is the method Eman is most
comfortable with, and should provide the most accurate though slowest)
recovery.

We could also infuse Sigmund with an earlier version of his pattern, either
from his rod or by summoning it from a previous version of him.  Riskier,
due to bandwidth constraints and the fun places he tends to get hurt in.

We could use Restore to Pattern to make a copy of the wounded Sigmund, and
replace him with it just before he was wounded.  A minor causality loop, but
the gods won't tell and we won't notice the difference.  Whatever the
doppelganger may have noticed is now, blessedly, a moot point.  Riskier
magically, but much safer for Sigmund.

We could also Discipline him, defining him as whole and unwounded, trickier,
but safer for him than for us.

If none of that works, I'll just get some mortar and a trowel...


                     -Myth.

