"RE: Game Mechanics","Game MechanicsWARNING: Long diatribe

Personally I (Pookie) am divided on this issue.  The core issue that I see
in Chris's last post is a game-playing issue rather than a game-universe
issue.  In most respects I am a proponent of gaming being a cooperative
venture where each player has the greatest freedom and support from other
players to develop there own characters except that Alex harshly rules over
all of us limiting our characters from the true world dominating potentially
that they obviously have :-).

This position however places me on both sides of this issue.  The reason can
be seen in the following two examples:

1.    Sigmund is a Fortu and at the same time is also (secret information)
Nureyev.  As such the nature and origin of Fortu are fundamental to his
character.  Kheldar is one of the five and was involved very closely when
the Fortu first came into existence.  Therefor this is also fundamental to
his character.

2.    Sigmund used to be Nureyev who used to be the Kua-Toa
Olactalan-Tlovanu (or at least so I assert).  Even though my Kua-Toa
heritage is in my dimly buried past and I do not have good memories about it
I have taken as strong interest in describing the Kua-Toa.  One major aspect
of the Kua-Toa (as I assert it) is that they are deathly enemies of the
Slaad.  As such I have done some describing of the Slaad.  I am not sure
what the source of his information was but Odin/Kheldar/Chris?  had a
slightly different impression of the nature of the Slaad as a race.

In the first case I think Kheldar and Sigmund have rationalized their
world-views (which are very relevant as they are now both within the active
memory of the characters).  By some degree of compromise, some degree of
just agreeing not to examine certain issues to closely and some degree of
leveraging the ever-useful reality shift to explain why both interpretations
of certain issues are true depending on which side of a reality shift you
are standing on.   I can't speak for Chris but from my perspective I feel
like we are not completely unified in world-view but it is working well.

In the second case I think I have leveraged the fact that the thing we had
different opinions about was so long ago and so dimly remembered that it is
not suprising our characters memories are different.  Also, becuase of the
nature of the third epoch - as demonstrated by our recent run,  I think that
it is perfectly consistent that both interpretations be the truth about
reality for different people at the same time (it was a fuzzier world back
then).

In truth, I use the same philosophy when it comes to elves.  Specifically
there are a number of things that Mordenaith thinks are impossible that I
believe are possible and a number of things that he thinks are hard that I
think are easier (probably not easy).  Over the course of the game I have
just chalked this up to (a character's) perception of reality generates the
rules that they operate against.  I am not saying we can all just decide to
do anything but I am saying that it didn't seem inconsistent to me that
different characters would operate under different rules and limitations
(including to some extent fundamental principles of magic) based on their
worldview.

Anyway, to put an end to a long diatribe and bring this back into the realm
of talking about game-playing:

I think that it is a wonderful gaming opportunity for each character to be
able to guide the development of their character (within the parameters set
by Alex).  I also recognize that becuase we operate in the same consensual
universe (and we are getting mighty big as entities in the universe go) we
have interdependancies and things I assert about my character will have
implications on your character and vice versa.

As such I think it is good if we all work together to rationalize our
worldviews but I also think that it needs to be acceptable for me to dictate
my characters view about what the Truth is about Odin and Mordenaith and
have this be different than these respective characters self perception.

This is all spoken from the perspective that there is no such thing as
player knowledge - only character knowledge and there is no TRUTH, only
truth relative to a specific worldview.

