You can philosophize all you want, but unless you can show me that 
you are right by doing something that most sane people think is 
impossible, then I'll take it for granted that we live in the same 
world, with the same history and the same rules.

Pookie, if you (or anyone that you know) can go astral at 10:00 PM 
Friday night and tell Shapeshifters what I am doing at that moment, 
I'll be more receptive to real-world differences in philosophy.

As for the game world, we (the Players) have an advantage that the 
characters (and people in the real world) do not.  For discussion 
purposed, we (the Players) can KNOW what really happened at a 
specific event without needing to be concerned about what Joe's view 
of the event was versus Jill's view of the event.  Those things do 
come into play, but since we are making up the event AND Joe's view 
of the event AND Jill's view of the event, we do not have the same 
advantage that people in the real world have: a common event from 
which different people remember or know different things.

To have the game make any sense at all we MUST agree on a common set 
of facts from which to form different opinions of WHY those events 
happened.  Without that common set of facts we waste each others time 
and become homicidally frustrated.  Well, I do anyway.

