Actually what it does say is that the particle really does have ALL possible
masses until you can prove it doesn't.  This is a mind bending concept for
me and I have been wrestling with it for years with no success.  A more
relevant example is Schroedinger's Cat.

Modern physics says the following thing: Put a cat in a box with a vial of
poison gas that will be released when hit by a gamma ray and also put in the
box a radioactive isotope with a half-life of a thousand years.  Now close
the box.  It is impossible to predict (by the nature of radioactive decay)
when a gamma ray will be released.  Note that physics does not say we are
not smart enough to predict but that it is impossible to predict.  Quamtum
mechanics says that until you open the box the cat is BOTH alive and dead.
Both realities are simultaneously true and the quantum wave will not
collapse until an observer measures the resulting system by openning the
box.  It makes my brain hurt.

Note that physics examples never worry about things like the ASPCA or the
cat starving to death.
